WiDS Missing Values

Math 4180

2/1/2021

Problem Definition

In the Women in Data Science (WiDS) Datathon 2021, we will build a model to determine whether a patient has been diagnosed with Diabetes Mellitus within the first 24 hours of being admitted to an Intensive Care Unit (ICU). To improve a patients outcome in an ICU knowledge about their medical conditions can improve clinical decisions. However, often a patients medical records are not immediately available due to transfer times. An additional challenge is when a patient is not able to provide such information due to their health condition, e.g.shock or unconsciousness. Therefore, it is important to be able to diagnose whether a patient has chronic diseases based on data that can be gathered within the first 24 hours of being admitted to an ICU.

Diabetes Mellitus

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) Diabetes Mellitus, or commonly know as diabetes, is defined as follows:

Diabetes is a chronic disease that occurs either when the pancreas does not produce enough insulin or when the body cannot effectively use the insulin it produces. Insulin is a hormone that regulates blood sugar. Hyperglycaemia, or raised blood sugar, is a common effect of uncontrolled diabetes and over time leads to serious damage to many of the bodys systems, especially the nerves and blood vessels. - WHO Diabetes Fact Sheet

There are two types of diabetes - Type 1 diabetes and Type 2 diabetes. Type 2 diabetes is more common than Type 1 diabetes and often results from excess body weight and physical inactivity while Type 1 diabetes is independent on body size. Additionally, there is Gestational diabetes in which a woman without diabetes develops high blood sugar levels during pregnancy. The latter usually resolves after birth while the other two types of diabetes have to be treated in the long-term.

Around 8.5% of the adult population is diagnosed with Diabetes independent of the gender (World Health Organization, 2020).

Diabetes mellitus is characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period of time and is diagnosed by demonstrating any one of the following:

  • Fasting plasma glucose level 7.0 mmol/L (126 mg/dL)
  • Plasma glucose 11.1 mmol/L (200 mg/dL) two hours after a 75 gram oral glucose load as in a glucose tolerance test
  • Symptoms of high blood sugar and casual plasma glucose 11.1 mmol/L (200 mg/dL)
  • Glycated hemoglobin (HbA1C) 48 mmol/mol ( 6.5 DCCT %)

Data Overview

The data is provided by MITs GOSSIS (Global Open Source Severity of Illness Score) initiative. It contains:

  • 179 features from 6 feature categories: identifier, demographic, APACHE co-variate, vitals, labs blood gas, APACHE co-morbidity
  • 1 target diabetes_mellitus

Read in our data

You will need to install the janitor,skimr and naniar packages if you do not have them.

library(tidyverse)
library(readr) #for reading in data
library(janitor) #for tably function (similar to table function)
library(skimr) # for skim function (similar to summary function)
library(naniar) #for missing values

We need to read in our data. You can download the TrainingWiDS2021 and DataDictionaryWiDS2021 here. If you keep it in your Downloads folder, you can use the following code chunk. If you keep this .Rmd file and the data sets in the same folder and set that as your working directory, you can just refer to the data by its name ie read_csv(TrainingWiDS2021.csv)

training <- read_csv("~/Desktop/math4180/TrainingWiDS2021.csv")
dictionary <- read_csv("~/Desktop/math4180/DataDictionaryWiDS2021.csv")

Missing Data

Next, lets use the var_miss function to see where missingness occurs. Since our dataset is so large, we can either downsample our data (use less of it) using the command sample_frac(size=0.8) or warn the vis_miss function that the data coming in is quite large using the warn_large_data=F argument (or both!)

Vitals

training %>%
  sample_frac(size=0.8) %>%
  select(contains(vitalnames[3])) %>%
  vis_miss(warn_large_data = F)

training %>%
  select(contains(vitalnames[3])) %>%
  gg_miss_upset(nsets=15)

BMI

According to the World Health Organization, BMI, or body mass index, is a known risk factor for diabetes1 . Although BMI is often advocated as a simple measure to determine disease risk, it has several limitations 2. BMI can be calculated as the ratio of weight(kilograms) to height squared (meters squared).

Lets try replacing the missing values with the mean for height and weight respectively. This technique is called imputing. Two techniques for doing this include using an ifelse() function or using the coalesce() function inside of a mutate() command.

training %>%
  mutate(___ = ifelse(___,mean(___, na.rm = TRUE),___)) %>%
  mutate(___ = coalesce(___, mean(___, na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  skimr::skim(___, ___)

Question 13

The above code chunk has one glaring misuse of data. What would you have to include to the code chunk to fix this issue?

Lets also add in BMI information. If we fix our mistake from the previous code chunk and have all our heights and weights filled in, we can actually use these values to calculate BMI rather. Add a mutate command to the fixed code chunk to do this.

Altogether our code should be in the form:

training%>%
  mutate(___ = replace_na(___,___)) %>%
  mutate(___ = replace_na(___, ___)) %>%
  group_by(___)%>%
  filter(___ !=___) %>%
  mutate(___ = coalesce(___, mean(___, na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  mutate(___ = coalesce(___, mean(___, na.rm = TRUE)))%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(___ = (___/(___)^2)) %>%
  skimr::skim(___, ___, ____, ___)
training%>%
  mutate(gender = replace_na(gender,"Unknown")) %>%
  mutate(ethnicity = replace_na(ethnicity, "Other/Unknown")) %>%
  group_by(gender)%>%
  filter(gender!="Unknown") %>%
  mutate(new_height = coalesce(height, mean(height, na.rm = TRUE))) %>%
  mutate(new_weight = coalesce(weight, mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE)))%>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(new_bmi = (new_weight/(new_height/100)^2)) %>%
  skimr::skim(gender, height, weight, new_height, new_weight, bmi, new_bmi)
